05:05.812 --> 05:07.947
Sorry, sir, can't release the rooms.

05:07.981 --> 05:10.216
Don't look now, but I think
someone famous just came in!

05:14.154 --> 05:17.356
Even better! It's Mercedes Jones!

05:17.390 --> 05:18.657
I was hoping you'd make it!

05:18.692 --> 05:20.459
Are you crazy? I wouldn't
miss this for the world.

05:20.494 --> 05:22.328
Ooh, I heard that you got a record contract

05:22.362 --> 05:23.729
because either Usher, Kelly Clarkson

05:23.763 --> 05:25.664
or Michael Jackson's daddy

05:25.699 --> 05:29.101
bought your album in
a 7-Eleven parking lot.

05:29.135 --> 05:31.637
<i>MERCEDES: I was selling my CD
Hell 2 the No in a parking lot.</i>

05:31.671 --> 05:34.640
<i>Now, I ain't gonna lie, business was wack.</i>

05:34.674 --> 05:37.009
<i>But then this Mexican lady bought one.</i>

05:37.043 --> 05:38.777
<i>I think she felt sorry for me.</i>

05:38.812 --> 05:41.914
<i>Turns out, that Mexican angel
on earth was the housekeeper</i>

05:41.948 --> 05:42.915
<i>to Kanye West.</i>

05:42.949 --> 05:44.550
<i>She gave it to Kanye,</i>

05:44.584 --> 05:47.052
<i>who gave it to Kim, and she
gave it to Ryan Seacrest,</i>

05:47.087 --> 05:50.623
<i>who gave it to Sony
Records... the Sony Records.</i>

05:50.657 --> 05:52.191
<i>Next thing I know, I'm sipping Perrier</i>

05:52.225 --> 05:53.452
<i>with a bunch of rich dudes.</i>

05:53.452 --> 05:54.885
All right, I like this plan,

05:54.920 --> 05:56.854
and I love that you guys like my songs.

05:56.888 --> 05:59.156
So, yes, I'll write for
the artists on your label.

05:59.191 --> 06:01.358
But there is a catch, so listen up.

06:01.393 --> 06:03.961
In exchange for six songs,
I want my own album deal.

06:03.995 --> 06:07.098
And I'm talking all the perks,
all the P&A that you can muster

06:07.132 --> 06:08.999
and two music videos that you pay for.

06:09.034 --> 06:10.401
And if it sells,

06:10.435 --> 06:13.237
I don't have to do a lame
follow-up Christmas album.

06:13.271 --> 06:15.072
Hold up.

06:15.107 --> 06:16.173
Is that dog alive?

06:16.208 --> 06:18.042
Oh, it's a faux-huahua.

06:18.076 --> 06:19.577
A fake Chihuahua.

06:19.611 --> 06:20.578
(laughs)

06:20.612 --> 06:22.146
Mr. Shue, Mercedes is here!

06:22.225 --> 06:23.926
- Oh, hey, Mercedes.
- Hi!

06:23.960 --> 06:26.128
I'd like to speak to a manager, please.

06:26.163 --> 06:27.463
What seems to be the problem here?

06:27.497 --> 06:28.998
WOMAN: Well, one hour ago,

06:29.032 --> 06:32.434
I got a call from Detective Sue Sylvester

06:32.469 --> 06:35.337
with the LAPD saying that
a 50-year-old Ohio man

06:35.372 --> 06:39.675
with a perm had abducted 12
emotionally disturbed teenagers,

06:39.709 --> 06:41.944
and if he tried to make a reservation,

06:41.978 --> 06:43.479
I was to contact the FBI.

06:44.848 --> 06:46.982
Oh, my God, that's them.

06:47.017 --> 06:49.151
Who?

06:49.186 --> 06:51.287
Do you seriously have no idea who that is?

06:51.321 --> 06:53.189
Do none of you read the show choir blogs?

06:53.223 --> 06:54.323
No, Blaine, we don't.

06:54.357 --> 06:56.659
None of us read the show
choir blogs. Just you.

06:56.693 --> 06:58.127
That's Throat Explosion.

06:58.161 --> 07:01.297
And that's their leader, Jean-Baptiste.

07:02.866 --> 07:05.067
Jean-Baptiste was born in
Quebec to acrobatic parents.

07:05.101 --> 07:07.736
He trained with Cirque du Soleil
before emigrating to Ft. Wayne

07:07.771 --> 07:09.338
where he used his
French-Canadian circus stylings

07:09.372 --> 07:11.307
to turn the entire show
choir world upside down.

07:11.341 --> 07:13.242
Bonjour !

07:13.276 --> 07:15.211
You must be the New Directions.

07:15.245 --> 07:18.180
And you... must be Blaine.

07:18.215 --> 07:21.283
How did you know my name?

07:21.318 --> 07:23.018
Show choir blogs.

07:23.053 --> 07:24.720
I'm, you know, I'm Sam Evans,

07:24.754 --> 07:26.522
and I'm the leader of the New Directions.

07:26.556 --> 07:29.225
And, you know, I know you guys
are all really good and stuff,

07:29.259 --> 07:31.527
but that's just gonna get
us out of our comfort zones

07:31.561 --> 07:32.761
and send us over the top.

07:32.796 --> 07:35.397
Well, it was really great to meet you, Sam.

07:35.432 --> 07:36.866
Best of luck, New Directions.

07:36.900 --> 07:39.869
We really can't wait to see your set.

07:39.903 --> 07:42.304
And crush you like a bug.

07:43.540 --> 07:44.573
Bye!

07:45.776 --> 07:46.976
Excuse me.

07:47.010 --> 07:48.577
What is with the turtlenecks?

07:52.349 --> 07:53.716
That was tense.

07:53.750 --> 07:58.053
Oh, I wouldn't miss this
show choir high school drama.

07:58.088 --> 08:00.189
Come on, tell me all about it. Let's go.

08:00.223 --> 08:02.324
Like a bug. That was good.
He was right here in my face.

08:02.359 --> 08:03.426
Why didn't I think of that?

08:03.460 --> 08:04.527
He smells like a winner.

08:12.269 --> 08:14.136
MAN (on TV): Another golden day
of sunshine here in Los Angeles.

08:14.171 --> 08:17.339
Hey, Marley, it's Ryder.
Can I come in for a minute?

08:21.011 --> 08:22.545
- Hi.
- Hi.

08:22.579 --> 08:24.547
Can I talk to you?

08:24.581 --> 08:26.382
- You can come in.
- Okay.

08:29.152 --> 08:32.554
Look, you and me are
probably never gonna happen.

08:32.589 --> 08:35.624
And... like, I'm slowly accepting that.

08:35.659 --> 08:38.394
But that doesn't mean
I don't care about you.

08:38.428 --> 08:40.029
Or that I don't occasionally look

08:40.063 --> 08:41.931
at your Facebook page to check your status.

08:41.965 --> 08:43.765
Single, and it's going to stay that way.

08:43.799 --> 08:45.601
Talking about where you
put what your job is.

08:45.635 --> 08:47.403
It used to say, "Singer/Songwriter,"

08:47.437 --> 08:49.071
now it just says "Undecided."

08:51.074 --> 08:54.777
I entered my songs into this contest.

08:54.811 --> 08:56.479
And you lost?

08:56.513 --> 08:59.882
Worse. I didn't hear back at all.

09:00.917 --> 09:02.251
And I took that as...

09:02.285 --> 09:03.753
I don't know... a wake-up call.

09:03.787 --> 09:05.788
Oh, come on. That's only one contest.

09:05.822 --> 09:09.592
Actually, I've entered a
bunch of contests, Ryder.

09:09.626 --> 09:12.828
Anyway, what's so wrong
with joining Accounting Club

09:12.863 --> 09:14.096
when we get back?

09:14.131 --> 09:16.031
(chuckles) Uh...

09:16.066 --> 09:17.399
I'll tell you one thing.

09:17.434 --> 09:19.702
I think, uh, Accounting Club
interferes with Glee Club.

09:21.571 --> 09:23.506
Marley, are you planning
on quitting Glee Club?

09:26.977 --> 09:29.078
I didn't want to let anyone down.

09:30.981 --> 09:33.816
And since this is going to be my swan song,

09:33.850 --> 09:35.651
I just want it to be fun.

09:35.685 --> 09:37.820
So, please, don't tell anyone.

09:41.625 --> 09:44.193
Are you sure we should be doing this?

09:44.227 --> 09:45.554
I mean, if we get caught...

09:45.564 --> 09:46.564
Oh, just go!

09:46.598 --> 09:48.332
Trust me, when I was in the Warblers,

09:48.367 --> 09:50.501
sneaking onto stage the night
before a show was tradition.

09:50.535 --> 09:52.837
We had other traditions, but
I can't really speak of them.

09:52.871 --> 09:54.171
We're not doing anything wrong.

09:54.206 --> 09:55.706
We're just, you know, getting a feel

09:55.741 --> 09:57.441
for the layout of the stage... our stage.

09:57.476 --> 09:59.777
So should we sing a song or hold hands

09:59.811 --> 10:01.212
or say a prayer or something?

10:01.246 --> 10:02.413
Because if I'm being honest,

10:02.447 --> 10:04.115
this ghost light's kind of freaking me out.

10:04.149 --> 10:06.250
All right, everybody,
circle up. I have a surprise.

10:09.254 --> 10:13.324
Finn Hudson made us a promise
at the beginning of the year:

10:13.358 --> 10:16.794
that we were all going
back to nationals together.

10:16.828 --> 10:18.629
Even when we lost sectionals,

10:18.663 --> 10:21.999
which was totally not Marley's fault,

10:22.034 --> 10:23.801
Finn told us that it wasn't over.

10:23.835 --> 10:27.605
He said that we'd be right here, together.

10:27.639 --> 10:32.043
Now, maybe you're
thinking, "Finn isn't here."

10:37.883 --> 10:40.418
Well, he is.

10:40.452 --> 10:43.020
I made sure of it.

10:43.055 --> 10:44.588
JEAN-BAPTISTE: Well, well!

10:44.623 --> 10:47.525
Les Directions Nouveau !

10:47.559 --> 10:49.460
Uh, apparently, we had the same plan

10:49.494 --> 10:51.696
for an illegal midnight rehearsal.

10:51.730 --> 10:52.463
"We?" You're alone.

10:52.497 --> 10:53.731
Am I?

10:53.765 --> 10:56.100
Existentially, yes, Blaine.

10:56.134 --> 10:57.301
Perhaps.

10:57.336 --> 10:58.402
We are all alone.

10:58.437 --> 11:00.571
But tonight, tonight,

11:00.605 --> 11:03.040
this stage belongs to us

11:03.075 --> 11:05.142
from midnight until dawn.

11:05.177 --> 11:07.545
You see, I called in a
few show choir favors.

11:07.579 --> 11:09.313
So, we'll just give you three minutes

11:09.348 --> 11:11.582
to gather your feelings and leave.

11:11.616 --> 11:12.783
Who is that?

11:13.685 --> 11:14.452
Your spirit guide?

11:14.486 --> 11:15.953
Dolph, enough.

11:15.987 --> 11:17.555
Have some respect.

11:20.792 --> 11:23.361
Look, everyone knows
you're that show choir.

11:23.395 --> 11:25.997
And everyone knows it's been
a very rough year for you.

11:26.031 --> 11:29.867
And now everyone is just waiting

11:29.901 --> 11:33.237
and watching... you.

11:33.271 --> 11:36.273
Tonight, you have our
condolences, New Directions.

11:36.308 --> 11:38.442
But let's just be very, very clear.

11:38.477 --> 11:40.678
Tomorrow, you will not have

11:40.712 --> 11:42.913
our mercy, pity or restraint.

11:43.782 --> 11:46.050
We are Throat Explosion.

11:46.084 --> 11:48.085
Expect us!

11:51.223 --> 11:52.189
Seven, eight!

11:52.224 --> 11:54.225
(feet stomping rhythmically)

12:03.359 --> 12:05.327
- How'd you learn to do that?
- Have you met my son Kurt?

12:05.361 --> 12:07.262
I cannot believe this
is our last competition.

12:07.296 --> 12:08.697
I am not ready for this to end.

12:08.731 --> 12:09.831
Do not start crying again.

12:09.866 --> 12:11.333
I'm not gonna cry.

12:11.367 --> 12:13.535
It's just that some of
my best memories from Glee

12:13.569 --> 12:15.303
- are these competitions.
- BURT: Yeah, well, you know what?

12:15.338 --> 12:17.105
That's why guys love
playing sports so much.

12:17.140 --> 12:19.107
It's not so much about
the winning and the losing.

12:19.142 --> 12:20.575
It's about going to war with your buddies.

12:20.610 --> 12:21.877
You know? The camaraderie.

12:21.911 --> 12:23.512
That's right. That's why you see a bunch

12:23.546 --> 12:25.280
of 50-year-old men humping
around a softball field

12:25.314 --> 12:26.715
or playing flag football.

12:26.749 --> 12:27.883
They're trying to recreate that feeling

12:27.917 --> 12:28.950
they're never gonna get back.

12:28.985 --> 12:29.985
Oh, my God, yes!

12:30.019 --> 12:31.219
That's it. Ugh.

12:31.254 --> 12:32.954
It's so depressing.

12:32.989 --> 12:34.823
I can't believe this
is our last competition.

12:34.857 --> 12:36.992
My life's gonna be so empty from now on.

12:37.026 --> 12:38.593
At least you get to have one.

12:42.065 --> 12:43.865
Oh, my God. I can't believe I said that.

12:43.900 --> 12:45.033
I am so sorry.

12:45.068 --> 12:46.068
No. It's okay.

12:46.102 --> 12:47.069
I'm sorry.

12:47.103 --> 12:48.470
That was totally insensitive of me.

12:48.504 --> 12:50.639
- Tina always does this.
- No, no, no.

12:50.673 --> 12:52.507
It's fine, honey, really.
You didn't do anything wrong.

12:52.542 --> 12:54.076
BURT: You know what,
guys? Why don't you go?

12:54.110 --> 12:56.078
And, uh, you go practice or something,

12:56.112 --> 12:58.080
and I'll have Carole finish up the sewing,

12:58.114 --> 13:01.350
and I'll drop the dress by your room, okay?

13:01.384 --> 13:03.051
Relax.

13:03.086 --> 13:04.987
No eating anything from
the minibar; it's expensive.

13:05.021 --> 13:07.589
If you want something,
go down to the 7-Eleven.

